I use the following set of elisp codes to switch from Japanese to
Korean; it uses iso-2022-kr as the file coding system, though.
--
(require 'korean)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*mail.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(set-default-file-coding-system *iso-2022-kr*); change here to *euc-kr*
(set-display-coding-system *euc-kr*)
(set-keyboard-coding-system *euc-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*inews.*" *euc-kr*)
(define-service-coding-system "nntp" nil *euc-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*scan.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*inc.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*mhl.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*anno.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(define-program-coding-system nil ".*rcvstore.*" *iso-2022-kr*)
(setq mh-before-send-letter-hook
      '(lambda () (set-file-coding-system *iso-2022-kr*)))
(setq vm-mode-hooks
      '(lambda ()
	(set-file-coding-system *iso-2022-kr*)))
(global-set-key "\C-\\" 'quail-mode)
(setq mh-letter-mode-hook
      (list (function (lambda ()
			(setq mail-header-separator "--------")
			;;(setq sc-preferred-header-style 1)
			))))
(set-korean-environment)
--

Change the third line to:
(set-default-file-coding-system *euc-kr*)

I used to use RMAIL while I was in the US with a normal sendmail,
and it worked perfectly. scan/inc/mhl/anno/rcvstore lines and (setq
mh-*) lines all concerns MH, and they may not be of your interest, so
just ignore them.

You may want to put the above into site-init.el and recompile (or
dump) your mule.

(The reason why I chose *iso-2022-kr* as the default is that you, with 
EUC, need to set the encoding system to *euc-jp* or *euc-kr* everytime 
you read a file in.)

