	I had experience using it on Unixware 2.01 PE + DEV pkg.
	as well as apps server pkg.

	Just follow the readme file.

	xmkmf and make will build hanterm

	then make install (if you're the root); or
	just keep a copy in your ~/bin.

	Now, if you're root use the 'bdftopcf' to build hangul fonts
	and install those into X11's font's misc dir then run 'mkfontdir'.

	Or, just create your own font dir such as ~/fonts; then keep it
	there by running 'mkfontdir'.

	Then play with xset +fp if you're using non-regular font path.

	Make sure where your X server can access your fonts: i.e. if you're
	using X font server, install those fonts into font server.

	X client (hanterm in this case) does not need to locate fonts; but
	when hanterm specifies the font name to use to X server, your X server
	has to locate those fonts and draw them in your face.

	BTW, both X that came with Unixware along with Motif and XFree86
	worked fine.

