I'll include below the unicode and utf-8 manual page, which I have
sent yesterday to the man page maintainer (together with the
m[un]lock[all] manuals). This is only introductory information about
what Unicode and UTF-8 is.

Here is a quick introduction into how Unicode support will works for
the programmer:

You can switch the console into UTF-8 mode (ESC % G) and upload any
256 character subsets of unicode into the VGA font buffer. This is
were the kernel is affected. Also some file system drivers (MS-DOS,
OS/2) will require UTF-8 conversion functions in the kernel.

The rest of the UTF-8 support needs do be done in libc and in some
application software, and a lot of work still has to be done there! At
the moment, practically none of the many ISO C (with ISO C Amendment 1
from 1994) library functions for wide character support have been
implemented in the Linux libc.

The plan essentially is:

The wchar_t values should always be Unicode values (or more precisely
the ISO 10646 BMP with implementation level 1, as we do not want to
mess around with complicated Korean encodings and combining characters
in general system tools). This should be independent of the locale in
order to guarantee binary compatibility for the wchar_t strings stored
in executables.

The locale will specify a "system character encoding". The system
character encoding is the encoding used for plain text files, file
names, stdout/stderr program messages, environment variables, etc. As
internal data structures in your software, you can either use the
system character encoding in type char or directly Unicode in type
wchar_t. The currently widely used system character encoding is ISO
8859-1 (Latin-1).

When Unicode support is ready, you can use the environment variable
LC_CTYPE in order to switch the system character encoding from Latin-1
to UTF-8. This will influence (currently unimplemented) functions like
wctomb/wctomb/wprintf/etc., which will convert wchar_t strings either
to Latin-1 or UTF-8 depending on LC_CTYPE, and back.

When enough software has become UTF-8 capable (most programs require
no changes, important changes only have to be made in xterm, editors,
and the curses library), then you will just use a program which
converts any 8-bit characters in existing text files from Latin-1 to
UTF-8 and then you set LC_CTYPE to e.g. "utf-8" and start to enjoy
live in a Unicode/UTF-8 system.

The details of UTF-8 support in software need a little bit more
explanation, may be it is time to write a Unicode-HOWTO ...

Essentially, in a Unicode software, you will write things like

  wprintf(L"Hello, world!\n");

Here L"Hello, world!\n" is of type wchar_t * and is a Unicode string.
This means that L"Hello, world!\n" could also contain Greek, Cyrillic
and Japanese text together. wprintf() calls internally wctomb() in
order to convert this Unicode string to the external "system character
encoding" (today Latin-1, later UTF-8, depending on the value of
LC_CTYPE). In case your software just prints English US-ASCII
messages, there will be no need to replace printf() by wprintf(),
because UTF-8 is like Latin-1 fully ASCII-compatible.

When gcc compiles the above program line, it will use internally
mbtowc() at compile-time, in order to transform the L"Hello, world!\n"
string into the wchar_t * 16-bit string constant which it puts into
the binary. This means that you will be able to use UTF-8 in C
strings, comments, etc if you have set LC_CTYPE correctly.

If a software wants to find out, whether the current system encoding
is Latin-1 or UTF-8, then it should just send a test character to
wctomb() and look at the result. The interpretation of the LC_CTYPE
string (e.g. whether it contains a substring "utf-8") should only be
done in libc, in order to make this easier exchangeable when ISO
finally has specified standard locale names.

If you want to learn more about wide character programming in ANSI/ISO
C, you should have a look at "C - A Reference Manual" from
Haribson/Steele (see below). If you read there "wide character set",
think of Unicode, and if you read there "multibyte characters" than
think of UTF-8. (ISO C is more generic and does not require UTF-8,
just as it does not require ASCII.)

