Danny Smith.  MInfTechSt, P/GDipInfTech, BSc, JP(Qld)
Operational Manager, AUSCERT.

Danny Smith graduated from The University of Queensland with a Bachelor of
Science degree during 1983.  His undergraduate years saw Danny become 
keenly interested in data security, which was developed during vacation 
contract employment.  Upon graduation, he was employed by the Prentice
Computer Centre doing operating system support for mini-computers.  During
this time, he performed detailed work on device drivers, real-time
processing systems, and network interface drivers. 

In 1985, he moved to the Communications group where he worked on many
aspects of networking including X.25, DECnet, ANF-10, and RSCS. During this
time, he was involved with the security of the University's networks,
implementing many intrusion detection procedures.

During 1987 and 1988, he worked at the Rutherford Appleton Laboratory in
the United Kingdom doing research with electronic mail systems and
directory services,  His project resulted in an electronic mail system that
consulted a directory for name to address resolution.  During this time, he
also consulted to various groups on networking and security issues.

Upon his return to Australia, Danny continued his work in networking and
security at the University.  He chaired the Working Group that developed
Access Control for the 1992 X.500 standard.  He was the defect editor for
that standard for many years.  It was also during this time that he
completed a Post Graduate Diploma in Information Technology at The
University of Queensland.

During 1992, Danny contracted to various organisations, developing software
ranging from device driver and protocol support, to information processing
systems.  He continued his consulting role in security to various
organisations during this time.

On 8 March 1993, the Security Emergency Response Team (SERT) was formed as
a cooperative of The University of Queensland, Queensland University of
Technology, and Griffith University, with Danny as the Operational Manager
responsible for its technical formation.  In August of that year, SERT was
admitted as a member of the Forum of Incident Response and Security Teams
(FIRST), with Danny as the FIRST Representative.

On 1 April 1994, a contract was commenced between The University of
Queensland and the Australian Vice-Chancellor's Committee to provide
security services for the Australian Academic Research Network (AARNet). 
This team was formalised as the Australian Computer Emergency Response Team
(AUSCERT), once more with Danny as the Operational Manager.  Since that
time, Danny has been elected to the FIRST Steering Committee.

In 1994, Danny received his Masters of Information Technology Studies from 
The University of Queensland.  His studies majored in computer security and 
data encryption.  Part of these studies were completed at the Information 
Security Research Centre, Queensland University of Technology.

Danny has lectured on OSI, Network Management, and Security to postgraduate
and undergraduate levels, and provided seminars on security to various user
groups, conferences, and organisations.  He has consulted on security in
Australia and overseas, and written several reports on aspects of security.
He is a member of IFIP Technical Committee 11, Working Group 4 which is 
studying the topic of Network Security.

