There are three standard encodings used in Japan for text files. They
are:
	Shift-JIS, used on almost all PCs.
	EUC-JP, used on some UNIX boxes.
	JIS(ISO-2022-JP), used on other Unix boxes and this has been
	 the network standard up to now.

ISO-2022-JP has been recommended as the encoding for inter-site
emails, and encoding conversion from local standard encodings,
ie. Shift-JIS or EUC-JP, are usually processed in user's mailer
process before messages are passed to sendmail. Similarly, encoding
conversions from ISO-2022-JP to local standards are processed with
user's mail reader process, not by popd nor other system processes.

In mailing on many UNIX boxes, editor processes usually save messages
in ISO-2022-JP and then no more conversion would be necessary. This is 
probably what Mr. Woohyong Choi stated in the above portion.

On windows/Mac or other personal computer systems, mailers seem to use 
native Shift-JIS encoding internally but they convert it to
ISO-2022-JP or whatever was set in the preferrence before passing the
mail bodies to SMTP hosts.

By the way, I'd once seen a site which used Shift-JIS oriented PCs as
terminal emulators and EUC was used for local file system standard but 
emails were perfectly encoded in ISO-2022-JP during being transferred.

IMHO, one of the the reasons Japanese sites agreed to use ISO-2022-JP
as the mail standard may be the existence of three major encodings. If
you have only two, then you can easily try the right one after the
first failure. The main reason was that sendmail had not been
8bit-clean, and still it's not always 8bit-clean in the real world.

