 TC2	TCSEC B3 시스템 개발(John McHugh/포트랜드주립대) 
  강의개요 : This tutorial will provide an overview of an approach to build-
ing trusted software based on confronting and meeting the risks involved. It
will begin with an overview of the software engineering process as seen in 
the commonly  used "waterfall" model which envisions an orderly progression,
without feedback, from requirements through specification, design, implemen-
tation, testing, and deployment.
  We then contrast this with the risk driven or spiral model which emphasizes
exploratory approaches to provide early resolution of issues that pose a high
degree of risk. In this context, risk may be characterized as a potential for
the system to meet some or all of its requirements for security, performance,
us ability, maintainability, etc. In tailoring this model to the development
of secure systems, we look at risk mitigation techniques that provide assura-
nce that designdecisions will result in a   secure system or that will help
to point out flaws that will prevent the system from meeting its goals. These
include the use of formal specifications and their analysis, the construction
of prototypes, and the use of security specific techniques such as covert ch-
annel analysis.  
  We illustrate the approach with an account of the development of a prototype
of a multilevel secure version of the X window system, TX. This system was
developed to show that usable high assurance windowing systems could be built.
It was intended to be certifiable at the B3 level of the US Trusted   Comput-
ing Systems Evaluation Criteria(TCSEC). The prototype is the basis for the
windowing system incorporated into Trusted Information Systems' TMACH operat-
ing system. The initial TX design was subjected to a variety of analyses that
showed it to be deficient in a number of ways. Analysis of these deficiencies
required a variety of mitigation techniques ranging from the construction of
formal models of the X protocol to covert channel analysis applied to multil-
evel cut and paste operations. We will show how each of these analysis helped
to provide evidence that the initial design was unsuitable for a high assura-
nce secure system. We will also show how these results helped to lead to a
much better design. The student should come away from the tutorial with an
appreciation for the some of the problems that are associated with building
trusted systems and an understanding of some of the techniques that can be
applied to gain assurance early in the development cycle.
 강사소개 : John McHugh is an associate professor and chairman of the Computer
Science Department at Portland State University in Portland, Oregon where he
holds a Tektronix Professorship. His research interests include computer sec-
urity, software engineering, and programming languages.
  He has previously taught at The University of North Carolina and at Duke
University. He has been a member of the editorial board of the IEEE Transact-
ions on Software Engineering and is the past Chair of the IEEE Technical Com-
mittee on Security and Privacy. He is the Program Chair of the 1966 IEEE Com-
puter Society Symposium on Security and Privacy.
